replies.bodyText:
Generally you are right and I tried it but in some cases (which seem pretty obvious) it returns null those cases are like:

audio/mp3
text/csv

Here https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12473851/how-i-can-get-the-mime-type-of-a-file-having-its-uri/12473985 where that solution is marked as accepted people also complain about the same.
Maybe I should use what you mentioned first and then in case of null my: mimeType.substring(mimeType.lastIndexOf("/") + 1);
or better yet (as a second step) I can read filename that should contain file extension:
        Cursor cursor = getContentResolver().query(fileUri, null, null, null, null);
        if (cursor != null && cursor.moveToFirst()) {
            name = cursor.getString(cursor.getColumnIndex(MediaStore.MediaColumns.DISPLAY_NAME));
        }
        String extension = name != null ? name.substring(name.lastIndexOf(".") + 1) : "";

this is what this library does https://github.com/anggrayudi/SimpleStorage. I know it's new and didn't gain traction yet but i ran into it through this topic https://stackoverflow.com/questions/63080879/get-file-extension-using-android-storage-access-framework.
What do you think?

